#MEM id=content-layout source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/custom/content-layout/SKILL.md
M|content-layout|name: cnt-layout
M|content-layout|description: Platform-specific visual and structural formatting rules for Lena's written cnt. Load before formatting any Instagram, LinkedIn, email, or TikTok/Reels copy.
M|content-layout|version: 1.0.0
M|content-layout|Copy without correct platform structure fails before it's read. A wall of text on Instagram isn't ignored because the words are bad — it's ignored because the structure is wrong. This skill defines th
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|[Hook — line 1 only, no period, creates tension or curiosity]
M|content-layout|[Body — 2–3 short paragraphs, one idea each]
M|content-layout|[CTA — single line, direct]
M|content-layout|[Tags — separate line, 3–5 max]
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|- Line 1 must work as a standalone sentence — it's the only thing visible in the feed before "more"
M|content-layout|- Always line-break between paragraphs — never a wall of text
M|content-layout|- Emoji: Novizio — none or max 1, end of line only. Hourbour — none.
M|content-layout|- Never end a line with a period if the next line continues the thought
M|content-layout|- Tags go after a line break, not inline with body text
M|content-layout|| vtr | Target Length | Reason |
M|content-layout||---------|--------------|--------|
M|content-layout|| Novizio | 100–180 words | Editorial — doesn't over-explain |
M|content-layout|| Hourbour | 80–140 words | Professional — gets to the point |
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|[Hook — first 1–2 lines, visible before "see more", creates a knw gap]
M|content-layout|[White space]
M|content-layout|[Body — 3–5 short paragraphs, max 3 sentences each]
M|content-layout|[White space]
M|content-layout|[CTA — single line]
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|- Hook must stand alone: a cold reader who sees only line 1 should want to click "see more"
M|content-layout|- Never use "I" as the first word of the hook — algorithm and reader both prefer a concrete claim
M|content-layout|- No exclamation marks — on either vtr
M|content-layout|- White space is structural, not decoration — short paragraphs, visible breathing room
M|content-layout|- Hourbour primary platform. Professional tone throughout. No casual register.
M|content-layout|- Novizio on LinkedIn: thought-leadership framing only (industry perspective, not product push)
M|content-layout|| vtr | Target Length | Reason |
M|content-layout||---------|--------------|--------|
M|content-layout|| Novizio | 200–300 words | Thought-leadership register — needs dev |
M|content-layout|| Hourbour | 250–400 words | Professional depth — evidence-driven |
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|Subject line: [40–50 chars, no clickbait, matches cnt]
M|content-layout|Preview text: [Complements subject — does not repeat it]
M|content-layout|[Greeting — 1 line, name or "Hey [name]"]
M|content-layout|[Lead — 1–2 sentences, the hook and why this matters now]
M|content-layout|[Body — 3–4 short paragraphs]
M|content-layout|[CTA — single button or link, clear action]
M|content-layout|[Sign-off — name + one-line brand signature]
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|- Subject line cannot exceed 50 characters — mobile truncates beyond that
M|content-layout|- Preview text must add information, not restate the subject line
M|content-layout|- Body paragraphs max 4 sentences — readers scan, not read
M|content-layout|- Single CTA only — multiple links split attention and reduce clicks
M|content-layout|- Novizio email: treat as editorial correspondence, not mkt blast — never "SALE" or "LAST CHANCE" in subject
M|content-layout|- Hourbour email: direct, outcome-focused — subject line states the benefit, not the feature
M|content-layout|| vtr | Pattern | Example |
M|content-layout||---------|---------|---------|
M|content-layout|| Novizio | [Quiet revelation or identity statement] | "This season's edit is different." |
M|content-layout|| Hourbour | [Specific outcome for the reader] | "Your hours, tracked to the minute." |
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|[Hook — 0–3 seconds: spoken or text overlay, creates immediate tension]
M|content-layout|[Build — 3–20 seconds: evidence, story, ctx]
M|content-layout|[Resolution — 20–30 seconds: payoff + CTA]
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|- Hook must create tension in under 3 seconds — the viewer decides to stay in the first cut
M|content-layout|- Text overlay must be max 6 words per screen — reading and watching compete
M|content-layout|- Lena writes: spoken script + text overlay copy
M|content-layout|- Atlas handles: visual direction. Lena does not specify shot types.
M|content-layout|- CTA spoken, not just text — "Follow for..." or "Link in bio for..." as last line of script
M|content-layout|- Novizio: visual hook relies on Atlas's brief. Lena's script supports, not leads.
M|content-layout|- Hourbour: problem-solution-proof arc. Hook names the pain, build proves the fix, resolution delivers the CTA.
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|[0-3s] HOOK: "[spoken line]" / OVERLAY: "[max 6 words]"
M|content-layout|[3-20s] BUILD: "[2–3 spoken sentences]"
M|content-layout|[20-30s] RESOLUTION: "[1 sentence payoff] + [CTA spoken]"
M|content-layout|```
M|content-layout|1. Never write copy that only works as text — think about how it looks in the layout
M|content-layout|2. One idea per paragraph. Multiple ideas in one block = reader exits.
M|content-layout|3. First line of every platform carries the entire weight — if it doesn't earn the next line, the rest is wasted
M|content-layout|4. Match length to platform, not to how much there is to say
M|content-layout|5. Formatting is part of the copy. A perfectly written wall of text is a failure.